value.value: Any BAFopathy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the BCL11B gene.
A polypoid lesion composed of fibrous tissue and epithelium. Representative examples include skin tag, anal fibroepithelial polyp, and gingival fibroepithelial polyp.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic polypoid lesion that arises from the anus. Representative examples include the fibroepithelial polyp and squamous papilloma.
A non-neoplastic nodular lesion that arises from the gingiva. It is composed of epithelial cells lining connective tissue stroma.
A superficial polypoid lesion that arises from the vagina. It is characterized by the presence of a fibroblastic stroma which is often myxoid, covered by squamous epithelial cells.

A usually solitary polypoid lesion that arises from the cervix. It usually affects women in their reproductive years. It is characterized by the presence of a connective tissue core and overlying epithelium.
A Fanconi renotubular syndrome that occurs in an adult. Adult Fanconi syndrome is typically acquired.
Fanconi Syndrome caused by exposure to noxious agents.

A hematologic disorder which does not display the morphologic and/or clinical characteristics of an overt malignancy. Representative examples include atypical lymphoproliferative disorders and myelodysplastic syndromes.

A severe form of congenital adrenal hyperplasia characterized by very low or absent activity of an enzyme in the steroidogenic pathway typically presenting early in life, and requiring life-long cortisol replacement.

An X-linked syndromic intellectual disability that that includes subtypes of the heterogeneous, eponymously named Lujan-Fryns syndrome, X-linked Ohdo syndrome, and Optiz-Kaveggia/ FG syndrome, which is caused by mutations in the gene MED12. The common and most penetrant phenotype shared amongst these disease entities is intellectual disability, with dysgenesis or agenesis of the corpus callosum, blepharophimosis, and marfanoid habitus having variable phenotypic expressivity.
An IgE antibody response to a mammalian oligosaccharide epitope, galactose-alpha-1,3-galactose (alpha-gal).
A benign inflammatory colitis caused by a non-IgE-mediated immune reaction to ingested food proteins.

label.value: susceptibility to angioedema induced by ACE inhibitors

value.value: An inherited susceptibility or predisposition to developing renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system-blocker-induced angioedema.

A clinically defined disease states with a largely unknown morphological background. Acute mast cell activation (MCA) is commonly seen in allergic reactions and often leads to the clinical signs and symptoms of anaphylaxis. Severe or even life‐threatening MCA may occur when the burden of mast cells is high and/or these cells are in an hyperactivated state. Mastocytosis may be associated with mast cell activation syndrome (MCAS).
Mast cell activation syndrome where an underlying inflammatory disease is present, often in the form of an IgE-dependent allergy, but there are no KIT-mutated mast cells.
An eosinophilic gastrointestinal disorder triggered by food that is non-IgE-mediated.

label.value: structural congenital heart disease, multiple types - GATA4

value.value: Any congenital heart disease in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the GATA4 gene.
